data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false"). Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // CollectionAssert for collection-specific checks
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

    // IsTrue is fine for predicate checks, but add a message
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use IsNotNull instead of Assert.IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure reports *"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"* instead of just *"Assert.IsTrue failed"*
- **`Assert.IsNotNull(obj)`** — semantically clearer than `IsTrue(x != null)`
- **`CollectionAssert`** — offers `Contains`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, `AreEqual` (order-sensitive), `AreEquivalent` (order-insensitive), etc.
- **Failure messages** — always add a message string to `IsTrue` predicate checks
- **`SingleOrDefault`** — avoids an exception before your assertion even runs if no match exists

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList); // same items, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);      // same items, same order
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset);
```
